in the medical field what is an osteopath an osteopath is a doctor who has had training similar to that of an md the philosophy of osteopaths differs from that of an md in that osteopaths believe in the body s innate ability to heal itself thus the osteopath will consider the whole patient rather than the symptoms a doctor of osteopathy can prescribe drugs perform surgery and use all scientifically accepted methods to treat their patients doctors of osteopathic medicine dos practise a whole person approach which means they consider both the physical and mental needs of their patients this holistic approach to health care was actually developed by an american md dr andrew taylor still feared that th century medicine was doing more harm than good disgusted at the ineffectiveness of fellow practitioners during the civil war he decided to focus on the body's ability to heal itself and began to stress preventive medicine Alternative medicine Naturopathic medicine Physician Traditional Chinese medicine Reiki Chiropractic Homeopathy Medical school Stomach cancer Natural health Psychiatry General practitioner Psychotherapy Doctorate Cancer Health science Quackery Prostate cancer Chronic fatigue syndrome Meditation Bipolar disorder Urinary incontinence Physical therapy Ayurveda Insomnia Transsexuality Reparative therapy Common cold Drug abuse Church of Christ, Scientist Faith healing Addiction Hypoglycemia Psoriasis Hypnosis Iridology Health profession Abortion Asthma Triage Traumatic brain injury Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma History of medicine Stroke Patent medicine Medical prescription Nurse Psychology Diabetes mellitus Sigmund Freud Epilepsy Dentistry Anorexia nervosa Subluxation Medieval medicine Practices of Jehovah's Witnesses Mental Health Act 1983 Ethics Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder Stress (medicine) Psychopharmacology Medical record Folic acid Orthopedic surgery Prayer Migraine Neuro-linguistic programming Neurofeedback Mental illness Involuntary commitment A